Replaces the wrapped value with a new one, returning the old value, without deinitializing either one.

This function corresponds to [`std::mem::replace`](../mem/fn.replace.html).

##### [Â§](#panics)Panics

Panics if the value is currently borrowed.

##### [Â§](#examples-2)Examples

```
use std::cell::RefCell;
let cell = RefCell::new(5);
let old_value = cell.replace(6);
assert_eq!(old_value, 5);
assert_eq!(cell, RefCell::new(6));
```

[Run](https://play.rust-lang.org/?code=%23!%5Ballow(unused)%5D%0Afn+main()+%7B%0A++++use+std::cell::RefCell;%0A++++let+cell+=+RefCell::new(5);%0A++++let+old_value+=+cell.replace(6);%0A++++assert_eq!(old_value,+5);%0A++++assert_eq!(cell,+RefCell::new(6));%0A%7D&edition=2021)

Replaces the wrapped value with a new one computed from `f`, returning the old value, without deinitializing either one.

##### [Â§](#panics-1)Panics

Panics if the value is currently borrowed.

##### [Â§](#examples-3)Examples

```
use std::cell::RefCell;
let cell = RefCell::new(5);
let old_value = cell.replace_with(|&mut old| old + 1);
assert_eq!(old_value, 5);
assert_eq!(cell, RefCell::new(6));
```

Swaps the wrapped value of `self` with the wrapped value of `other`, without deinitializing either one.

This function corresponds to [`std::mem::swap`](../mem/fn.swap.html).

##### [Â§](#panics-2)Panics

Panics if the value in either `RefCell` is currently borrowed, or if `self` and `other` point to the same `RefCell`.

##### [Â§](#examples-4)Examples

```
use std::cell::RefCell;
let c = RefCell::new(5);
let d = RefCell::new(6);
c.swap(&d);
assert_eq!(c, RefCell::new(6));
assert_eq!(d, RefCell::new(5));
```

[Run](https://play.rust-lang.org/?code=%23!%5Ballow(unused)%5D%0Afn+main()+%7B%0A++++use+std::cell::RefCell;%0A++++let+c+=+RefCell::new(5);%0A++++let+d+=+RefCell::new(6);%0A++++c.swap(%26d);%0A++++assert_eq!(c,+RefCell::new(6));%0A++++assert_eq!(d,+RefCell::new(5));%0A%7D&edition=2021)

1.0.0 Â· [source](https://doc.rust-lang.org/1.80.0/src/core/cell.rs.html#977)

Immutably borrows the wrapped value.

The borrow lasts until the returned `Ref` exits scope. Multiple immutable borrows can be taken out at the same time.

##### [Â§](#panics-3)Panics

Panics if the value is currently mutably borrowed. For a non-panicking variant, use [`try_borrow`](#method.try_borrow).

##### [Â§](#examples-5)Examples

```
use std::cell::RefCell;

let c = RefCell::new(5);

let borrowed_five = c.borrow();
let borrowed_five2 = c.borrow();
```

1.13.0 Â· [source](https://doc.rust-lang.org/1.80.0/src/core/cell.rs.html#1012)

Immutably borrows the wrapped value, returning an error if the value is currently mutably borrowed.

The borrow lasts until the returned `Ref` exits scope. Multiple immutable borrows can be taken out at the same time.

This is the non-panicking variant of [`borrow`](#method.borrow).

##### [Â§](#examples-6)Examples

```
use std::cell::RefCell;

let c = RefCell::new(5);

{
    let m = c.borrow_mut();
    assert!(c.try_borrow().is_err());
}

{
    let m = c.borrow();
    assert!(c.try_borrow().is_ok());
}
```

[Run](https://play.rust-lang.org/?code=%23!%5Ballow(unused)%5D%0Afn+main()+%7B%0A++++use+std::cell::RefCell;%0A++++%0A++++let+c+=+RefCell::new(5);%0A++++%0A++++%7B%0A++++++++let+m+=+c.borrow_mut();%0A++++++++assert!(c.try_borrow().is_err());%0A++++%7D%0A++++%0A++++%7B%0A++++++++let+m+=+c.borrow();%0A++++++++assert!(c.try_borrow().is_ok());%0A++++%7D%0A%7D&edition=2021)

1.0.0 Â· [source](https://doc.rust-lang.org/1.80.0/src/core/cell.rs.html#1073)

Mutably borrows the wrapped value.

The borrow lasts until the returned `RefMut` or all `RefMut`s derived from it exit scope. The value cannot be borrowed while this borrow is active.

##### [Â§](#panics-4)Panics

Panics if the value is currently borrowed. For a non-panicking variant, use [`try_borrow_mut`](#method.try_borrow_mut).

##### [Â§](#examples-7)Examples

```
use std::cell::RefCell;

let c = RefCell::new("hello".to_owned());

*c.borrow_mut() = "bonjour".to_owned();

assert_eq!(&*c.borrow(), "bonjour");
```

[Run](https://play.rust-lang.org/?code=%23!%5Ballow(unused)%5D%0Afn+main()+%7B%0A++++use+std::cell::RefCell;%0A++++%0A++++let+c+=+RefCell::new(%22hello%22.to_owned());%0A++++%0A++++*c.borrow_mut()+=+%22bonjour%22.to_owned();%0A++++%0A++++assert_eq!(%26*c.borrow(),+%22bonjour%22);%0A%7D&edition=2021)

1.11.0 Â· [source](https://doc.rust-lang.org/1.80.0/src/core/cell.rs.html#1173)

Returns a mutable reference to the underlying data.

Since this method borrows `RefCell` mutably, it is statically guaranteed that no borrows to the underlying data exist. The dynamic checks inherent in [`borrow_mut`](about:blank/struct.RefCell.html#method.borrow_mut "method std::cell::RefCell::borrow_mut") and most other methods of `RefCell` are therefore unnecessary.

This method can only be called if `RefCell` can be mutably borrowed, which in general is only the case directly after the `RefCell` has been created. In these situations, skipping the aforementioned dynamic borrowing checks may yield better ergonomics and runtime-performance.

In most situations where `RefCell` is used, it canâ€™t be borrowed mutably. Use [`borrow_mut`](about:blank/struct.RefCell.html#method.borrow_mut "method std::cell::RefCell::borrow_mut") to get mutable access to the underlying data then.

##### [Â§](#examples-10)Examples

```
use std::cell::RefCell;

let mut c = RefCell::new(5);
*c.get_mut() += 1;

assert_eq!(c, RefCell::new(6));
```

[Run](https://play.rust-lang.org/?code=%23!%5Ballow(unused)%5D%0Afn+main()+%7B%0A++++use+std::cell::RefCell;%0A++++%0A++++let+mut+c+=+RefCell::new(5);%0A++++*c.get_mut()+%2B=+1;%0A++++%0A++++assert_eq!(c,+RefCell::new(6));%0A%7D&edition=2021)

[source](https://doc.rust-lang.org/1.80.0/src/core/cell.rs.html#1199)

ðŸ”¬This is a nightly-only experimental API. (`cell_leak`Â [#69099](https://github.com/rust-lang/rust/issues/69099))

Undo the effect of leaked guards on the borrow state of the `RefCell`.

This call is similar to [`get_mut`](about:blank/struct.RefCell.html#method.get_mut "method std::cell::RefCell::get_mut") but more specialized. It borrows `RefCell` mutably to ensure no borrows exist and then resets the state tracking shared borrows. This is relevant if some `Ref` or `RefMut` borrows have been leaked.

##### [Â§](#examples-11)Examples

```
#![feature(cell_leak)]
use std::cell::RefCell;

let mut c = RefCell::new(0);
std::mem::forget(c.borrow_mut());

assert!(c.try_borrow().is_err());
c.undo_leak();
assert!(c.try_borrow().is_ok());
```

[Run](https://play.rust-lang.org/?code=%23!%5Ballow(unused)%5D%0A%23!%5Bfeature(cell_leak)%5D%0Afn+main()+%7B%0A++++use+std::cell::RefCell;%0A++++%0A++++let+mut+c+=+RefCell::new(0);%0A++++std::mem::forget(c.borrow_mut());%0A++++%0A++++assert!(c.try_borrow().is_err());%0A++++c.undo_leak();%0A++++assert!(c.try_borrow().is_ok());%0A%7D&version=nightly&edition=2021)

1.37.0 Â· [source](https://doc.rust-lang.org/1.80.0/src/core/cell.rs.html#1233)

Immutably borrows the wrapped value, returning an error if the value is currently mutably borrowed.

##### [Â§](#safety)Safety

Unlike `RefCell::borrow`, this method is unsafe because it does not return a `Ref`, thus leaving the borrow flag untouched. Mutably borrowing the `RefCell` while the reference returned by this method is alive is undefined behaviour.

##### [Â§](#examples-12)Examples

```
use std::cell::RefCell;

let c = RefCell::new(5);

{
    let m = c.borrow_mut();
    assert!(unsafe { c.try_borrow_unguarded() }.is_err());
}

{
    let m = c.borrow();
    assert!(unsafe { c.try_borrow_unguarded() }.is_ok());
}
```

[Run](https://play.rust-lang.org/?code=%23!%5Ballow(unused)%5D%0Afn+main()+%7B%0A++++use+std::cell::RefCell;%0A++++%0A++++let+c+=+RefCell::new(5);%0A++++%0A++++%7B%0A++++++++let+m+=+c.borrow_mut();%0A++++++++assert!(unsafe+%7B+c.try_borrow_unguarded()+%7D.is_err());%0A++++%7D%0A++++%0A++++%7B%0A++++++++let+m+=+c.borrow();%0A++++++++assert!(unsafe+%7B+c.try_borrow_unguarded()+%7D.is_ok());%0A++++%7D%0A%7D&edition=2021)

pub fn borrow(&self) -> Ref<'_, T>

Immutably borrows the wrapped value.

The borrow lasts until the returned Ref exits scope. Multiple immutable borrows can be taken out at the same time.

Â§Panics

Panics if the value is currently mutably borrowed. For a non-panicking variant, use try_borrow.

Â§Examples
use std::cell::RefCell;

let c = RefCell::new(5);

let borrowed_five = c.borrow();
let borrowed_five2 = c.borrow();

pub fn try_borrow(&self) -> Result<Ref<'_, T>, BorrowError>

Immutably borrows the wrapped value, returning an error if the value is currently mutably borrowed.

The borrow lasts until the returned Ref exits scope. Multiple immutable borrows can be taken out at the same time.

This is the non-panicking variant of borrow.

Â§Examples
use std::cell::RefCell;

let c = RefCell::new(5);

{
    let m = c.borrow_mut();
    assert!(c.try_borrow().is_err());
}

{
    let m = c.borrow();
    assert!(c.try_borrow().is_ok());
}

pub fn borrow_mut(&self) -> RefMut<'_, T>

Mutably borrows the wrapped value.

The borrow lasts until the returned RefMut or all RefMuts derived from it exit scope. The value cannot be borrowed while this borrow is active.

Â§Panics

Panics if the value is currently borrowed. For a non-panicking variant, use try_borrow_mut.

*c.borrow_mut() = "bonjour".to_owned();

pub fn get_mut(&mut self) -> &mut T

Returns a mutable reference to the underlying data.

Since this method borrows RefCell mutably, it is statically guaranteed that no borrows to the underlying data exist. The dynamic checks inherent in borrow_mut and most other methods of RefCell are therefore unnecessary.

This method can only be called if RefCell can be mutably borrowed, which in general is only the case directly after the RefCell has been created. In these situations, skipping the aforementioned dynamic borrowing checks may yield better ergonomics and runtime-performance.

In most situations where RefCell is used, it canâ€™t be borrowed mutably. Use borrow_mut to get mutable access to the underlying data then.

Â§Examples
use std::cell::RefCell;

let mut c = RefCell::new(5);
*c.get_mut() += 1;

assert_eq!(c, RefCell::new(6));
Run

pub fn undo_leak(&mut self) -> &mut T

ðŸ”¬This is a nightly-only experimental API. (cell_leak #69099)

Undo the effect of leaked guards on the borrow state of the RefCell.

This call is similar to get_mut but more specialized. It borrows RefCell mutably to ensure no borrows exist and then resets the state tracking shared borrows. This is relevant if some Ref or RefMut borrows have been leaked.

Â§Examples
#![feature(cell_leak)]
use std::cell::RefCell;

let mut c = RefCell::new(0);
std::mem::forget(c.borrow_mut());

assert!(c.try_borrow().is_err());
c.undo_leak();
assert!(c.try_borrow().is_ok());
Run

pub unsafe fn try_borrow_unguarded(&self) -> Result<&T, BorrowError>

Immutably borrows the wrapped value, returning an error if the value is currently mutably borrowed.

Â§Safety

Unlike RefCell::borrow, this method is unsafe because it does not return a Ref, thus leaving the borrow flag untouched. Mutably borrowing the RefCell while the reference returned by this method is alive is undefined behaviour.

Â§Examples
use std::cell::RefCell;

let c = RefCell::new(5);

{
    let m = c.borrow_mut();
    assert!(unsafe { c.try_borrow_unguarded() }.is_err());
}

{
    let m = c.borrow();
    assert!(unsafe { c.try_borrow_unguarded() }.is_ok());
}
